{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540240"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:52:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:52:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16751"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563374"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T22:57:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T22:57:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16751"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16751"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.02,0.91,0,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75516"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9442"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16751"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61028"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"3234"},{"type":"tags","id":"5958"},{"type":"tags","id":"9014"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22321"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25036"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75516"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of progressive slowness of movement and tremor. She has a history of schizophrenia treated with haloperidol for eight years until six months ago, when she was switched to risperidone due to poor control. Her current medications include risperidone, benztropine (commenced three months ago), venlafaxine, and metformin. She has no family history of movement disorders but her parent has type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has a symmetrical resting tremor of both hands, reduced arm swing bilaterally when walking, and cogwheel rigidity in both upper limbs. Her face appears less expressive than on previous visits. There are also intermittent choreiform movements of her tongue and perioral region that worsen when she is distracted. Blood tests including copper studies, liver function tests, and thyroid function tests are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Parkinson\u0027s disease with levodopa-induced dyskinesia","Multiple system atrophy with tardive dyskinesia","Drug-induced parkinsonism with tardive dyskinesia","Wilson\u0027s disease with orofacial dystonia","Huntington\u0027s disease with secondary parkinsonism"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a complex movement disorder with both parkinsonian features and dyskinesia. The history of long-term antipsychotic use, followed by the addition of an anticholinergic medication (benztropine) and a medication switch, creates a perfect scenario for \u003Cstrong\u003Edrug-induced parkinsonism with tardive dyskinesia\u003C/strong\u003E. The bilateral symmetrical parkinsonism and oro-bucco-lingual dyskinesias are characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParkinson\u0027s disease with levodopa-induced dyskinesia\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely given the patient\u0027s young age, the symmetrical onset, and absence of levodopa therapy. Additionally, levodopa-induced dyskinesias typically affect the limbs more than the oro-bucco-lingual region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple system atrophy with tardive dyskinesia\u003C/strong\u003E would be extremely unusual at this age and would typically present with prominent autonomic features. While tardive dyskinesia can occur in MSA patients treated with antipsychotics, the temporal relationship and age make this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWilson\u0027s disease with orofacial dystonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents earlier in life and would show copper metabolism abnormalities. While it can cause both parkinsonism and dystonia, the normal copper studies and liver function tests make this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuntington\u0027s disease with secondary parkinsonism\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely to present with such symmetric parkinsonism, and chorea in Huntington\u0027s typically affects the trunk and limbs more prominently than the oro-bucco-lingual region. The absence of cognitive decline or family history also makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe case illustrates how anticholinergic medications like benztropine can partially mask underlying drug-induced parkinsonism while potentially unmasking or exacerbating tardive dyskinesia. The long duration of typical antipsychotic use (haloperidol) followed by a switch to risperidone, along with the addition of benztropine, creates a complex picture of drug-induced movement disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Drug-induced parkinsonism from antipsychotic medications is typically bilateral and symmetric at onset, unlike Parkinson\u0027s disease.","The presence of dyskinesia alongside parkinsonism suggests tardive syndromes rather than Parkinson\u0027s disease.","Anticholinergic medications can mask underlying parkinsonism while causing tardive dyskinesia to become more prominent."],"references":["Benjamin JS, Kaplan SJ. Sadock Comprehensive Textbook of Psychiatry."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61028"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16751"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61028"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T09:05:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T09:12:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9442"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75516"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"